.TH "SOVEREIGN-OSCTL-SECURITY" "1" "2026-07-14" "sovereign-os 0.2.0" "sovereign-os Operator Manual"
.hy
.SH NAME
.PP
sovereign-osctl-security - security, identity, perimeter, and audit
.SH SYNOPSIS
.PP
\f[B]sovereign-osctl\f[R] \f[I]command\f[R] [\f[I]subcommand\f[R]]
[\f[I]options\f[R]]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
Tetragon perimeter, selfdef, Secure Boot, permission classification,
authentication tiers, hardening, network edge, peace-machine checks, and
security mirrors.
.PP
This page owns 18 top-level commands.
Ownership is defined in
\f[V]docs/man/sovereign-osctl-command-topics.json\f[R] and checked
against the real dispatcher.
\f[B]sovereign-osctl help\f[R] remains authoritative for the exact
syntax shipped by the installed version.
.SH SAFETY MODEL
.PP
Key generation, policy reloads, tier changes, firewall changes,
quarantine, trust, and grant operations affect the security boundary.
Inspect status, plans, diffs, and current policy before applying.
.PP
Read-only discovery should precede mutation.
JSON output, when offered, is the stable surface for automation; human
output is intended for direct operator use.
.SH COMMON WORKFLOW
.IP "1." 3
Inspect the relevant \f[B]status\f[R], \f[B]show\f[R], \f[B]list\f[R],
\f[B]info\f[R], \f[B]plan\f[R], or \f[B]doctor\f[R] surface.
.IP "2." 3
Save machine-readable output when \f[V]--json\f[R] is available.
.IP "3." 3
Review profile, device, backend, policy, and target selection.
.IP "4." 3
Apply the smallest scoped mutation.
.IP "5." 3
Re-run health/status and inspect alerts or journal output.
.SH EXAMPLES
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
sovereign-osctl perimeter verify
sovereign-osctl selfdef status
sovereign-osctl secure-boot status
sovereign-osctl audit drift --json
sovereign-osctl permission --mode auto \[aq]systemctl restart sovereign-gatewayd\[aq]
\f[R]
.fi
